
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `im-launch` baraye ejra kardane method-haye voroodi (input methods) dar Linux estefade mishavad. Yani be shoma komak mikonad ta betavanid zaban-haye mokhtalef ra type konid, mesle Farsi, Arabi, ya Chinese. ⌨️ In dastoor bishtar dar system-haye graphiki mesle X Window System karbord darad.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 Hich gozine-ye khas-i nadarad.  Vaghti ke `im-launch` ra ejra mikonid, system khodash method-e voroodi ra shoru mikonad. 🚀

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ im-launch

    🔹 Ba ejra kardane in dastoor, method-e voroodi shoru mishavad.  Agar motmaen nistid koja method-e voroodi ra bebinid, be donbale yek neshane dar system tray (kenar-e saat) begardid. 🔎

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ im-launch

    🔹 Ba ejraye in dastoor, shoma mitavanid bad az restart kardane computer, method-e voroodi ra dorost ejra konid. Agar zaban-e shoma dorost namayesh dade nemishavad, in dastoor mitavanad moshkel ra hal konad. 👍

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `im-launch` command is used to launch input methods in Linux. This allows you to type in different languages, such as Farsi, Arabic, or Chinese. ⌨️  This command is primarily used in graphical systems like the X Window System.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹  It doesn't have any specific options. 🚀 When you run `im-launch`, the system automatically starts the input method.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ im-launch

    🔹  Running this command starts the input method. If you're unsure where to see the input method, look for an icon in the system tray (near the clock). 🔎

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ im-launch

    🔹  By running this command, you can ensure the input method starts correctly after a computer restart. If your language isn't displayed correctly, this command can resolve the issue. 👍

